}}

'''Apollo 1''' (also designated '''Apollo Saturn-204''' and '''AS-204''') was scheduled to be the first manned mission of the [[Apollo program|Apollo manned lunar landing program]], with a target launch date of February 21, 1967. A cabin fire during a launch pad test on January 27 at [[Cape Canaveral Air Force Station Launch Complex 34|Launch Pad 34]] at [[Cape Canaveral Air Force Station|Cape Canaveral]] killed all three crew members: Command Pilot [[Gus Grissom|Virgil &quot;Gus&quot; Grissom]], Senior Pilot [[Edward Higgins White|Edward H. White]] and Pilot [[Roger Chaffee|Roger B. Chaffee]]; and destroyed the [[Apollo Command/Service Module#Command Module (CM)|Command Module]].&lt;ref name=&quot;MarAprChron&quot;/&gt;  The mission name ''Apollo 1'', chosen by the crew, was officially retired by [[NASA]] in commemoration of them on April 24, 1967.&lt;ref name=&quot;MarAprChron&quot;/&gt;

Immediately after the fire, NASA convened the '''Apollo 204 Accident Review Board''' to determine the cause of the fire. Although the ignition source was never conclusively identified, the astronauts' deaths were attributed to a wide range of lethal design and construction flaws in the early Apollo Command Module. The manned phase of the project was delayed for twenty months while these problems were corrected. 

The [[Saturn IB]] launch vehicle, SA-204, scheduled for use on this mission, was later used for the first unmanned [[Apollo Lunar Module|Lunar Module]] test flight, [[Apollo 5]].&lt;ref&gt;http://www.nasm.si.edu/research/arch/findaids/bellcomm/bci_sec_21.html&lt;/ref&gt; The first successful manned Apollo mission was flown by Apollo 1's backup crew on [[Apollo 7]] in October, 1968.

