'''Apollo 15''' was the ninth manned mission in the [[United States|American]] [[Apollo program|Apollo space program]], the fourth to [[Moon landing|land]] on the [[Moon]] and the eighth successful manned mission. It was the first of what were termed &quot;J missions&quot;, long duration stays on the Moon with a greater focus on science than had been possible on previous missions. It was also the first mission where the [[Lunar Roving Vehicle]] was used. 

The mission began on July 26, 1971, and concluded on August 7. [[NASA]] called it the most successful manned flight ever achieved.&lt;ref name=&quot;autogenerated1971&quot;&gt;[http://www.upi.com/Audio/Year_in_Review/Events-of-1971/12295509436546-1/#title &quot;Apollo 15: 1971 Year in Review, UPI.com&quot;]&lt;/ref&gt;

Commander [[David Scott]] and Lunar Module Pilot [[James Irwin]] spent three days on the Moon and a total of 18½ hours outside the spacecraft on lunar [[extra-vehicular activity]]. The mission was the first not to land in a [[Lunar mare]], instead landing near [[Mons Hadley|Hadley rille]] in an area of the [[Mare Imbrium]] called ''Palus Putredinus'' (Marsh of Decay). The crew explored the area using the first Lunar Rover, allowing them to travel much farther from the [[Apollo Lunar Module|Lunar Module]] lander than had previously been possible. They collected a total of 77&amp;nbsp;kg (170 [[pound (mass)|lbs]]) of lunar surface material.

At the same time, Command Module Pilot [[Alfred Worden]] orbited the Moon, using a Scientific Instrument Module (SIM) in the Service Module to study the lunar surface and environment in great detail with a panoramic camera, [[gamma ray spectrometer]], mapping camera, laser [[altimeter]], [[Mass spectrometry|mass spectrometer]], and lunar sub-satellite deployed at the end of Apollo 15's stay in lunar orbit (an Apollo program first).

== Crew ==
{{Spaceflight crew
|terminology      = Astronaut
|position1        = Commander
|crew1_up         = [[David Scott|David R. Scott]]
|flights1_up      = Third
|position2        = Command Module Pilot
|crew2_up         = [[Alfred Worden|Alfred M. Worden]]
|flights2_up      = Only
|position3        = Lunar Module Pilot
|crew3_up         = [[James Irwin|James B. Irwin]]
|flights3_up      = Only
}}

All three astronauts on the all-Air Force crew received either an honorary degree or Master's degree from the [[University of Michigan]], including Scott's honorary degree, awarded in the spring of 1971, just months before the launch. Scott did attend the University of Michigan, but left before graduating to accept an appointment to the US Military Academy. The crewmen did their undergraduate work at the US Military Academy or the US Naval Academy.

=== Backup crew ===
{{Spaceflight crew
|terminology      = Astronaut
|position1        = Commander
|crew1_up         = [[Richard F. Gordon, Jr.]]
|position2        = Command Module Pilot
|crew2_up         = [[Vance D. Brand]]
|position3        = Lunar Module Pilot
|crew3_up         = [[Harrison Schmitt|Harrison H. Schmitt]]
}}

Schmitt was the first member of [[NASA Astronaut Group 4|Group 4]] to be selected as either a prime or backup crew member for an Apollo flight.

